    id: 34,
    slug: "vercel-context-ai-oauth-breach-2026",
    title: "Vercel's Breach Came Through a Third-Party AI Tool an Employee Clicked 'Allow All' On",
    summary: "A Vercel staffer's broad OAuth grant to Context.ai gave attackers a path from a March AWS compromise into customer environment variables, exposing API keys for crypto and fintech developers.",
    body: [
      "One employee's 'Allow All' button. That is the entry point. On April 20th, Vercel disclosed that an attacker had accessed customer environment variables by chaining through Context.ai, a third-party AI productivity tool used internally, which had itself been breached in March via unauthorized access to its AWS environment.",
      "The attack chain is worth walking through because it reflects a pattern that will keep repeating. Context.ai offers an AI office suite that connects to Google Workspace. At least one Vercel employee authorized it using their corporate account with maximum OAuth scope. When attackers compromised Context.ai's infrastructure and obtained its stored OAuth tokens, that broad grant translated directly into control of the employee's Vercel Google Workspace account. From there, attackers pivoted into Vercel's internal environments and pulled project environment variables not flagged as 'sensitive' in the platform.",
      "Vercel's architecture separates sensitive-flagged variables into an encrypted store the attackers did not reach. What lived in the unsecured store: the things developers put into CI/CD pipelines assuming internal-only access — third-party API keys, database connection strings, service credentials. Crypto and fintech developers building on Vercel reported scrambling to rotate keys the same afternoon of disclosure. CoinDesk tracked the fallout in real time as developers cycled through their infrastructure looking for exposure.",
      "ShinyHunters posted a claim on BreachForums asking $2 million for the stolen data, then told BleepingComputer the group had nothing to do with it. Infostealers.com separately reported that the Context.ai breach originated from an infostealer infection at the company, meaning the attacker likely bought stolen credentials from a stealer log rather than breaking into Context.ai's systems directly. Vercel says the investigation is ongoing.",
      "The scope here extends well beyond Vercel. Context.ai serves hundreds of organizations. Any company whose employees authorized it with Google Workspace admin-level scope during the window of the March compromise is a potential victim of the same attack chain. Context.ai is one of thousands of AI productivity tools that have made 'connect your workspace' a core product feature, typically requesting the widest OAuth scopes the consent screen allows.",
      "Review your Google Workspace connected apps today. Pull the OAuth scope list, revoke anything with admin-level access that IT did not explicitly approve, and rotate credentials for any service whose keys might have lived in Vercel project settings. Going forward, treat every AI tool OAuth grant as a third-party vendor security review, not a convenience checkbox.",
    ],
