    id: 36,
    slug: "apache-activemq-cve-2026-34197-jolokia-rce-cisa-kev",
    title: "Attackers Found a 13-Year-Old RCE in Apache ActiveMQ's Management Interface",
    summary: "CVE-2026-34197 abuses ActiveMQ's Jolokia JMX-HTTP bridge to execute arbitrary code — effectively without credentials on certain 6.x versions — and CISA wants federal agencies patched by April 30.",
    body: [
      "The Jolokia management endpoint in Apache ActiveMQ has been shipping enabled by default for 13 years. CVE-2026-34197 is what happens when researchers finally pull on it.",
      "The vulnerability is a code injection flaw in the Jolokia JMX-HTTP bridge that ActiveMQ exposes for monitoring and administration. An attacker who can reach that endpoint can call the BrokerService MBean and force the broker to fetch a remote Spring XML configuration file they control. The JVM then executes it. CVSS score is 8.8, technically requiring low-privilege credentials — but that bar has a structural hole in it.",
      "On ActiveMQ versions 6.0.0 through 6.1.1, CVE-2024-32114 (a separate, widely undeployed patch) leaves the Jolokia API exposed with no authentication whatsoever. An organization that upgraded to the 6.x branch for its features but hasn't kept up with every subsequent patch is running what is functionally unauthenticated remote code execution. Default credentials (admin:admin) make it nearly as bad on many 5.x deployments where nobody has changed the defaults.",
      "Horizon3.ai disclosed the vulnerability after researchers used AI-assisted code analysis to trace the Jolokia invocation path as a viable attacker-controlled sink. A 13-year-old critical flaw sitting in a default-enabled management API, not found by prior manual audits. It's a reasonable argument for running AI-augmented code review across legacy open-source projects with large exposed attack surfaces.",
      "CISA added CVE-2026-34197 to the Known Exploited Vulnerabilities catalog and gave federal civilian agencies until April 30 to patch or disconnect affected systems. SAFE Security documented active exploitation against internet-exposed Jolokia endpoints, particularly deployments running default or no authentication.",
      "Patch to ActiveMQ 5.19.4 or 6.2.3. If patching isn't immediate, block external access to port 8161 (the admin console) at your firewall. Run a query on your IP ranges for exposed ActiveMQ instances (Shodan and Censys both index these) and assume any unpatched, internet-reachable broker with default credentials has already been touched.",
    ],
